    <patterns>
      <pattern name="DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS edit-in-place" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SlashCommandMenu/slashCommandMenu.types.ts">
        The `/summarize` entry sits at the top of the `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS`
        array (id: 'summarize', label: 'Summarize', trigger: '/summarize',
        icon: SparkleRegular, category: 'system', source: 'system'). The
        `description` field is the ONLY field that changes — current value
        "Summarize the current analysis document" → "Summarize uploaded files
        or the active document". Do NOT change id/label/trigger/icon/category/
        source — those are public API surface consumed by `useSlashCommands`
        + `useDynamicSlashCommands` and any test snapshots.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="SprkChat onSend handoff to host" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChat.tsx">
        `SprkChat`'s internal `handleSend(messageText)` (line ~913) is the
        single funnel for all user messages — including slash-command messages
        like "/summarize ..." that arrive as plain text after the
        `useSlashCommands` hook writes the trigger into the textarea and the
        user presses Enter / clicks Send. The host (`ConversationPane`)
        observes this flow via SprkChat's existing prop contract; tri-mode
        routing logic belongs at the ConversationPane layer (host-side intent
        recognition), NOT inside the shared `SprkChat` component (which would
        violate ADR-012 context-agnosticism). Mechanism: inspect the message
        prefix in ConversationPane's wrapping logic OR via a new optional
        callback prop, choosing whichever path produces the smallest surface
        delta with the existing component contract. Document the chosen
        approach in task notes.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Back-compat wizard flow entry point" location="src/solutions/LegalWorkspace/src/components/SummarizeFiles/SummarizeFilesDialog.tsx">
        The existing wizard flow is consumed via `SummarizeFilesDialog` in
        LegalWorkspace (and re-exported through `@spaarke/ui-components`'s
        `SummarizeFilesWizard` module). It opens as a modal dialog with its
        own SSE stream from `POST /api/workspace/files/summarize` per
        `summarizeService.ts`. The "active document" branch of tri-mode
        routing dispatches to this existing path; do NOT modify the wizard
        itself.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="ChatSession.UploadedFiles read site" location="src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Models/Ai/ChatSession.cs (per task 004)">
        Task 004 adds `UploadedFiles[]` to `ChatSession`. The frontend reads
        this via the existing AiSessionProvider / chat-session manifest API
        (whichever surface task 004 + task 020 expose). The tri-mode check is
        a simple length check at the dispatch site. If task 004 has not yet
        surfaced this property to the frontend at the time this task runs,
        coordinate via the parallel-task notes and use a temporary
        `(chatAttachments?.length ?? 0) > 0` check on the existing
        `chatAttachments` array as the closest analog — document the
        decision in task notes.
      </pattern>
      <pattern name="Deterministic chat interjection (assistant addMessage)" location="src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChat.tsx">
        SprkChat already supports adding assistant messages programmatically
        via the `addMessage` helper used inside `handleSend` (and elsewhere
        for action chips). For the "neither" branch, surface a programmatic
        interjection via the existing host-callable mechanism (the simplest
        approach is to push an assistant message before delegating to
        SprkChat OR via the predefined-prompt suggestion surface — design
        decision documented in task notes). The interjection is a single
        message; no streaming, no playbook invocation.
      </pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <context>
    <background>
      R5 ships chat-driven Summarize as its vertical-slice proof point. The slash
      command `/summarize` already exists from R3 and dispatches into the legacy
      LegalWorkspace wizard. R5 needs the slash command to serve a new, distinct
      mode (session-uploaded files) WITHOUT breaking the wizard mode. Per spec
      FR-03, the prompt-first ordering is one of the two valid upload flows: the
      user can type `/summarize` first, get told "Upload the file(s) you'd like
      me to summarize", upload files via the existing chip / attachment surface,
      and then receive a streaming summary in the Workspace pane. This task is
      the small but load-bearing glue that turns the slash command from a
      single-mode entry point into the tri-mode dispatcher the new UX requires.
      It's pure frontend, no BFF code changes, and the publish-size delta is
      exactly zero by construction.
    </background>
    <dependencies>
      <dependency task="004" status="parallel-or-prior">
        Provides `ChatSession.UploadedFiles[]` manifest on the model; the
        frontend reads `.length > 0` to make the tri-mode decision. If task 004
        has not yet surfaced the property to the frontend AiSessionProvider at
        runtime, task 019 falls back to the closest existing analog
        (`chatAttachments.length` on the SprkChat-managed in-memory attachments)
        and notes the bridge for task 020 (chat-pane orchestration UX) to align.
      </dependency>
      <dependency task="014" status="parallel">
        Provides `POST /api/ai/chat/sessions/{sessionId}/summarize` endpoint —
        the fallback path for explicit slash-command dispatch when LLM tool-
        calling is not invoked. Task 019 wires the routing decision to either
        the agent-tool path (LLM-mediated) or this endpoint (explicit slash).
      </dependency>
      <dependency task="015" status="parallel">
        Provides `InvokeSummarizePlaybookTool` agent-tool function — the
        natural-language path for Summarize. Task 019's slash-command dispatch
        and task 015's tool registration must produce identical output via the
        shared `SessionSummarizeOrchestrator` (task 012) — task 019 only needs
        to know that BOTH paths exist and dispatch correctly.
      </dependency>
    </dependencies>
    <related-work>
      <item>R3 shipped the original `DEFAULT_SLASH_COMMANDS` + `/summarize`
        wizard binding. R5 extends; does not replace.</item>
      <item>Plan.md D2-10 and spec FR-03 are the authoritative requirement
        sources for this task; the description text and interjection text are
        spec-driven, not implementer-chosen.</item>
      <item>Task 020 (D2-11 chat-pane orchestration UX — file chips, persistent
        indicator, per-file remove) is a sibling in P2-G5 and may run in
        parallel. Coordination point: if task 020 lands first, this task reads
        `ChatSession.UploadedFiles` via the surface task 020 exposed; if this
        task lands first, task 020 inherits the routing decisions intact.</item>
      <item>Task 021 (D2-12 "Summarize this only" per-file affordance) is also
        a P2-G5 sibling and provides the UI-button equivalent of tri-mode
        branch (a) — both must converge on the same orchestrator dispatch.</item>
    </related-work>
  </context>

